uhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the life course, new forms of community, ways of keeping in contact, and practices for engaging in work, healthcare, retail, learning and leisure are evolving rapidly. Breaking new ground in the study of technology and aging, this book examines how developments in smart phones, the internet, cloud computing, and online social networking are redefining experiences and expectations around growing older in the twenty-first century. Drawing on contributions from leading commentators and researchers across the world, this book explores key themes such as caregiving, the use of social media, robotics, chronic disease and dementia management, gaming, migration, and data inheritance, to name a few.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aOlder people. 0aTechnology and older people. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aAstell, Arlene J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Julie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Schutter, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelaney, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinsmore, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarattini, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarattini, Chiara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreenhalgh, Trisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct